      <scopecontent id="aspace_cc18d61157deb04cbc478094ca34d4d3">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Collection of 16 occult and astrology-themed ex libris, most by Slovakian artist, Karl Hugo Frech (1883-1945), created between circa 1920 and circa 1975. Includes examples of etching and woodcut, some litho printed.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_762831a063b0ab5efbfa02c81c665208">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The collection is open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <bioghist id="aspace_9367d9c5f8a20b15184f38bc912db423">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Karl Hugo Frech (1883-1945) was a graphic artist and painter known both for his depictions of Bratislava, where he spent most of his life, and for his bookplates, many of them occult-themed.</p>
         <p>Frech was born on September 9, 1883, in Stuttgart, Germany. He studied lithography at the G.F. Schreiber Art Institute in Esslingen, and attended the Academy of Applied Arts in Stuttgart (1903-1905), where he later worked. He also studied at the Academy of Fine Arts in Karlsuhe. After a period of European travel in Italy and Sweden, he married and moved to Bratislava (formerly known as Pressburger) in 1914. There, he was a member of the Pressburger Kunstverein and made his living as a painter and graphic artist. He contributed illustrations to books and newspapers, including Pressburger Zeitung and Grenzboten, and received numerous commissions for bookplates from notable figures in Bratislava. Many of his bookplate designs feature an occult theme.</p>
         <p>Frech died on July 27, 1945, near the Austrian town of Steyr, while attempting to escape from a camp for displaced Germans.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_0584b8fc27b5c5cb9ac4444fe47536e8">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Collection of occult bookplates, Robert B. Haas Family Arts Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
